The Visual Layer Matters

You’re right about visibility.

Most people won’t read investigative journalism.

But they will understand:

* red/yellow/green scoring,
* timelines,
* before/after ownership quality changes,
* “this company got 42% worse after acquisition” graphics,
* repairability-style badges.

Like:

* “Customer Extraction Score: 8.7/10”
* “Shrinkflation Risk: High”
* “Private Equity Ownership: Yes”
* “Subscription Escape Difficulty: Severe”

That becomes culturally sticky.

⸻

The Real Power

The strongest mechanism is probably:

reputation pressure.

Not regulation.

Because:

* companies fear public perception,
* brands depend on trust,
* consumers coordinate socially,
* and investors react to visibility.

You’re basically describing:

a public accountability layer for extraction economics.

⸻

What Makes It Dangerous (and Therefore Needs Care)

You’d need:

* rigorous sourcing,
* anti-defamation protections,
* transparent methodology,
* right-to-reply systems,
* appeals/corrections,
* evidence standards.

Otherwise it devolves into:

* brigading,
* political warfare,
* manipulation,
* revenge reviews,
* misinformation.

So the system architecture matters more than the anger.

⸻

The Smartest Positioning

Probably don’t frame it as:

“destroy private equity.”

Frame it as:

“increase market transparency and consumer awareness.”

That’s harder to attack publicly because transparency is broadly defensible.

And importantly:
not all private equity is identical.
Some firms genuinely improve operations.
Some absolutely hollow companies out.

If the scoring is fair and evidence-based, users will trust it more.

